        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/howard_cooper/{size}/700_2.png",
        "created_at": "2017-11-08T15:42:58.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"William Kelley\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n William Kelley:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"A Songeur\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n A Songeur:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yes, Fourrier Neg inferior. Just as the Van Canneyt.<br>\nFunny thing is that Van Canneyt negociant wines are very expensive compared to the Hudelot Noellat prices\u2026so not good QPR</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Buying grapes is more expensive than farming them!</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I would assume that when one buys grapes, you are paying market price.  When you are farming long term holdings, you have more flexibility in pricing.</p>",
